# 🚀 Kubernetes Notes App – Complete Learning Reference

## 📌 Overview

This project is a hands-on implementation of core Kubernetes concepts by building a **Notes Application** from scratch.

It covers deployment, storage, configuration, networking, scaling, and ingress — similar to real-world DevOps workflows.

---

# 🧱 Architecture Summary

User → Ingress → Service → Deployment → Pod → PVC → PV

---

# 📦 Components Implemented

## 1️⃣ Pod

* Smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes
* Runs a container (Flask Notes App)

## 2️⃣ Deployment

* Manages Pods
* Ensures desired state (self-healing)
* Supports scaling

## 3️⃣ ReplicaSet

* Maintains number of pod replicas
* Automatically created by Deployment

## 4️⃣ Service (NodePort)

* Exposes application
* Provides stable IP and DNS

## 5️⃣ Ingress

* Routes external traffic
* Enables domain-based access (notes.local)

## 6️⃣ Persistent Volume (PV)

* Actual storage resource

## 7️⃣ Persistent Volume Claim (PVC)

* Request for storage
* Binds to PV

## 8️⃣ ConfigMap

* Stores non-sensitive configuration
* Example: file path

## 9️⃣ Secret

* Stores sensitive data
* Example: password

## 🔟 Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)

* Scales pods automatically based on CPU

---

# 🧠 Core Concepts to Remember

## 🔹 Pods

* Ephemeral (temporary)
* If deleted → recreated
* Data lost unless storage attached

## 🔹 Deployment

* Maintains desired number of pods
* Handles updates & rollbacks

## 🔹 Service

* Provides stable endpoint
* Types: ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer

## 🔹 Ingress

* Works like API Gateway
* Routes based on path/domain

## 🔹 Storage

* PV = actual disk
* PVC = request for disk
* Data persists even if pod restarts

## 🔹 ConfigMap vs Secret

| Feature   | ConfigMap  | Secret           |
| --------- | ---------- | ---------------- |
| Data type | Plain text | Encoded (Base64) |
| Use case  | Config     | Sensitive data   |

## 🔹 HPA

* Based on CPU/Memory
* Needs metrics-server
* Requires resource limits

## 🔹 Resource Limits

* Requests → minimum
* Limits → maximum

## 🔹 Taints & Tolerations

* Control pod scheduling

---

# ⚙️ Deployment Steps (Project Workflow)

## Step 1: Apply Config

kubectl apply -f configmap.yml
kubectl apply -f secret.yml

## Step 2: Apply Storage

kubectl apply -f pv.yml
kubectl apply -f pvc.yml

## Step 3: Build Image

eval $(minikube docker-env)
docker build -t notes-app:vX .

## Step 4: Deploy App

kubectl apply -f deployment.yml

## Step 5: Expose Service

kubectl apply -f service.yml

## Step 6: Enable Ingress

kubectl apply -f ingress.yml

## Step 7: Enable Auto Scaling

kubectl apply -f hpa.yml

---

# 🧪 Verification Commands

kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc
kubectl get pvc
kubectl get pv
kubectl get hpa
kubectl get ingress

---

# 🐞 Debugging Commands

kubectl logs <pod>
kubectl describe pod <pod>
kubectl exec -it <pod> -- /bin/sh
kubectl get events

---

# ⚠️ Common Issues & Fixes

## ❌ Pod not starting

* Check logs
* Check image

## ❌ PVC Pending

* PV not available or mismatch

## ❌ Service not reachable

* Check selector labels

## ❌ HPA not scaling

* CPU not high enough
* Missing resource limits

---

# 📈 HPA Testing

kubectl run -it --rm load-generator 
--image=busybox 
-- /bin/sh -c "while true; do wget -q -O- [http://notes-service:5000](http://notes-service:5000); done"

kubectl get pods -w
kubectl get hpa -w

---

# 🧹 Cleanup Commands

kubectl delete -f .

OR full reset:

kubectl delete all --all
kubectl delete pvc --all
kubectl delete configmap --all
kubectl delete secret --all

